{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_jennet_ver02/data/sn95079130/00393348574/1949012001/0012.xml":{"full_text":"Dickenson County Herald\n(Xi.oTcenson County\u2019s Oldest J\\fezospaper 49\n_ c J subtend\nvm.invnf ntvk\nCLINTWOOD, VA., THURSDAY, JANUARY 20, 1949\nNUMBER THIRTY-THREE\nOf\nAll\nThings!\n\nREMARKABLE REMARKS\nMost people believe only halt\nof what they hear. Therefore, one\nhas to tell anything at least\ntwice as big as it really is to get\nit across. \u2014Relph Newberry\nIt is shocking that millions of\nour children are not receiving a\ngood education. Millions of them\nare in overcrowded and obsolete\nbuildings. \u2014President Truman\n\u201cPee Wee\u201d Phillips, \u201cPious\u201d\nFred Beverly, \u201cCriminal\" John\nHammonds and \u201cHawkeye\u201d Mul\nilins, guardians of the peace and\nmorals of this county, got a still\nand accessories on Bartlick last\nweek. Although they went in\nsight of Blue Head, they did not\ncross into that wild land \u201cwhere\nangels fear to tread.\u201d Phillips,\nwho was in command of the ma\nrauders, has a very healthy re\nspect for that line that was\ndrawn on him and bears in mind\nthat the law goes only to Bart\nlick.\n\nIf winter comes, can John L.\nLewis be far behind, to para\nphrase a line from Keats.\nMarquis Childs in Roanoke\nTimes.\nThe one left behind in this in*\nstance is Percy Byshee Shelley.\nAre you beginning to realize\nhow fortunate it is for ClintWood\ntht the town did not attempt too\nmuch, expansion during the boom\nperiod? There was a good deal of\nbuilding, but it was all needed\nand will continue to be needed.\nThere were some new business\nventures, but nearly all of them\nwere rock-bottomed and copper\nplated. There was a considerable\ngrowth in population, perhaps a\nbit too much, for the community\ncannot now give all the people\nemployment and essential ser\nvices. But that unhealthy margin\nis not as big as it might have\nbeen if the professional boosters\nhad had their way. The recession\nwill, of course, shake things\ndown a bit. But the shakedown\nwill not affect Clintwood as vi\nolently as it might have done.\nProbably no purely local business\nwill fail. The business places\nmay not make as much as they\nhad hoped, but they can keep\ngoing. After all, that is what\ncounts in the long run,\n\nThievery and burglarly go on\nand on in Clintwood. This is a\ndisgrace to the town. We, in the\nfriendliest spirit and in no criti\ncal vein, suggest to the city\nmothers who make up the gov\nerning body of this community\nthat they should study this situ\nation and find some means of\nstopping it.\n\nA colony is a community de\npending on the production of a\nraw material and dependent in\nall other respects. We plan to talk\nabout the colonial situation of\nour county next week.\nMall your news to early\nSTEINMAN NEGRO\nKILLED IN\nFRACAS\nRpy Smith, 30 years of age,\ncolored, was fatally stabbed at\nSteinman on Saturday night at\nabout eight o\u2019clock by Claude\nDurrah, Jr. He died almost in\nstantly.\nOfficers state that Smith, Dur\nrah and another Negro had been\nto Clinchco and returned to Stein\nman in a taxi. The cab stopped in\nfront of the home of Durrah\u2019s par\nents while the men were trying\nto arrange for payment of their\nfare. There is evidence to t h e\neffect that they had been drink\ning. An argument came up be\ntween Smith and Durrah and de\nveloped into a quarrel. Smith\nwas stabbed with a large knife\non the left side just above the\nheart. He walked into the Dur\nrah home and fell over a piece of\nfurniture. Although no vital or\ngan was touched, pressure from\nthe outside evidently caused the\nleix lung 10 couapse.\nDurrah fled from the place.\nT. M. Gibson, coal operator at\nSteinman, offered a reward of\n$200 for him. He was arrested\nnear Red Ridge tunnel, about a\nmile from Steinman, by two citi\nzens Sunday morning and was\nbrought to the jail in Clintwood.\nThe hearing in trial justice\ncourt was postponed for a week.\nIt is understood that Durrah will\noffer a plea of self-defense. It\nis also said that the slain man\nwas on parole from the state pen\nitentiary.\nThieves Still Break In\nAnd Steal\nClintwood had its usual week\nend attempt at burglary either\nSaturday or Sunday night. The\nHome Hardware was the intend\ned victim, but the robbery was\nnot carried to a successful con\nclusion.\n,A cierk returning to work Mon\nday morning, found the garage\ndoor, at the lower rear end of\nthe building had been opened.\nSince the door led into the gar\nage and nowhere else, the at\ntempt at robbery failed. The\nscrews had been taken out of the\ndoor and it was held in place\nonly by a bar. It is supposed that\nthe burglars pushed inside and\nfound themselves against a blank\nwall. So far as can be learned,\nthe only clue left was a track\nleft by a number eight shoe.\nA theft succeeded Monday\nnight, when a battery was taken\nfrom a wrecked Jeep in front of\nthe City Service Station in the\nwest end. The wreck had been\nhauled in and left in front of\nthe garage. No clues have been\nreported.\nFOOD AND APRON SALE\nThe senior Woman\u2019s Club and\nPTA are sponsoring a food and\napron sale Saturday afternoon,\nJan. 22, from to to 5 p. m., in the\nNewberry Building. All proceeds\nwild go to the March of Dimes.\nThere will be cakes, pies, cook\nies, salads and all kinds of home\ncooked food.\nMiss Thelma Hudson, of Hot\nSprings, Ark., spent the past\nweek visiting Mr. and Mrs. Joe\nKennedy.\nMail your news in early\nnt I\nwwiiu, frMtjd\n\"sbafej*\n525?\nsa\nMEANEST YET Gretchen,\n\u25a0ad-eyed dachshund owned by\nAllen Boyer of Chicago, views\nsign warning of pet poisoners.\nHer two canine playmates died\nafter eating meat containing\nground glass.\nPeople of River Road To\nAsk For Improvements\nThe people along Brush Creek\nand throughout the entire Moun\ntain Precinct have decided that\nwaiting does not always, pay.\nThey have, therefore, made up\ntheir minds to ask for some road\nimprovement.\nThe road running from Clint\nwood down Brush Creek and up\nPound River to Norland serves a\ngreat number of people and has\nsix feeder roads. A bus line, a\nschool bus line and a rural mail\nroute traverse this section. Pour\nchurches and eight stores are lo\ncated on this road. It was graded\nand based in 1937 by the WPA.\nSince last winter, this road has\nbecome washboarded and chug\nholed, passable but hard on mo\ntor vehicles.\nThose who dwell along and\nadjacent to this road fear that the\nbase will wear away, since it has\nstarted to crumble. They plan to\npresent a request through the\nBoard of Supervisors that hard\nsurfacing be applied, at least to\nthe mouth of Brush Creek. It is\nunderstood that an organizing\nmeeting for this purpose will be\ncalled at an early date.\nMr. and Mrs. Fred Carter left\non Tuesday of this week for\nFlorida.\nAged Nealy Ridge\nCitizen Dies\nFollowing Stroke\nJames Peter Reedy died in the\nDickenson County Hospital early\nTuesday morning. He was strick\nen with paralysis Saturday and\nremained in a semi-consious con\ndition until the time of his death.\nHe had been very unwell for the\npast year.\nThe deceased was born on\nNealy Ridge more than 76 years\nago, a son of Linville and Jane\nMillis Reedy. He was reared in\nthat community and lived there\nalii his life, never moving from\nthe farm where he was born. He\nwas married to Mary E. Ball in\n1889. He was a farmer and watch\nrepairman by occupation. Mr.\nReedy served three terms as jus\ntice of the peace in the Ervinton\nDistrict and was for one term a\nmember of the district school\nboard. He was a member of the\nFreewill Baptist church.\nBurial was at the old home\nplace on Nealy Ridge. Funeral ar\nrangements were in charge of the\nOlintwood Funeral Home and\nfloral offerings were supplied by\nthe Mountain Florist.\nSurviving are two sons, John\nWesley and Garland Reedy, and\nthe following daughters: Mrs.\nMolly Couch, Mrs. Rosa Dotson,\nMrs. Sarah Tichenor, Mrs. Ethel\nFranklin, Mrs. Armina Ega'n, Mrs\nPearl Perrigan, Mrs. Myrtle Ellis\nand Mrs. Belva J. Chaska.\nMRS. AYERS SHORTT\nENTERTAINS\nLast Friday evening at 7:30,\nMrs. Ayers Short entertained\nwith a tacky party at her home\nfor the benefit of the March of\nDimes. A penny for each inch\nof height was paid by each guest.\nMrs. Steve Coe won first prize\nfor having the tackiest dress\nwhile Mrs. A. A. Skeen, Sr., took\nsecond prize.\nIn the games, prizes went to\nMrs. Buford Barrett and Mrs.\nCurt Mullins. Special guests were\nMiss Thelma Hudson of Hot\nSprings, Ark., and Mrs. Cleo\nStrouth of North Carolina.\n\u201cDead\u201d For 20 Years;\nComes Home Again\nA man who had disappeared 20\nyears ago and had been long\nsince presumed dead reappeared\nat the home of a niece on Camp\nCreek Sunday, and was recogniz\ned by his relatives.\nThe man was Calvin Adding\nton, youngest son of the late Fil\nmore Addington. He came to the\nhome of his niece, Mrs. Jasper\nMullins, and announced himself.\nWord went out to his sisters in\nthe community and they rushed\nto identify the lost brother. He\nwas easily identified by relatives\nand former acquaintances and\ngave a simple account of his long\nabsence.\nIt appears that he married a\nshort while before he left. He\nand his wife did not hit it off well\nand he decided that he would try\nto find peace and satisfaction\nelsewhere. He went to Cincinnati,\nwhere he lived under an assumed\nname, working part of the time\nin a bottling plant and the re\nmaining time in a bakery. He re\nvealed his true name and circum\nstances to a special friend. This\nfriend on last Saturday called his\nattention to a newspaper adver\ntisement appealing to any rela\ntive of John Addington to come\nhome at once as the latter was in\na serious condition. John Adding\nton is Calvin Addington\u2019s older\nbrother. In response, he hastened\nback to his native community.\nAfter a lapse of seven years,\nVirginia law presumes that a per\nson who has disappeared with\nout trace is dead. While Adding\nton was away, his estate had\nbeen divided among his relatives.\nIf he wishes to reclaim his prop\nerty, he will have to go through\nthe courts to do so. His claim, if\nmade, will not be contested, as\nall relatives were overjoyed to\nsee him.\nHe learned that his wife had\nnot remarried and hastened to\nher home between Pound and\nWise, hoping to gain her consent\nto another trial at married life.\nQuantico, Va., Jan. 20\u2014Mar\nrine private first class Wili\nam P. Raines of Breaks, Va.,\nis marching today with the\nfamed 22nd Marine battalion\nduring the presidential inaugur\nal parade in Washington, D.C.,\nfollowing the inaugural cere\nmonies at the Capitol building.\nThe U. S- Marine Band,\nwhich has played at every in\nauguration since that of Pres\nident John Adams on New\nYear\u2019s Day, 1801, is included in\nthe Marine\u2019s participation.\nRaymond Reece Found\nDead In Home At\nFremont\nThe body of Raymond Reece,\n37, son of Orbin Reece, was found\nin his home at Fremont at 2 p.m.\nFriday, with a bullet hole through\nthe head.\nHe had not been seen since\nTuesday evening of last week.\nHis father, learning this, went to\nthe home to look for him. The\ndoors were locked and window\nshades drawn. Mr. Reece entered\nthe house through a window at\nthe back and found his son\u2019s body\non a bed. A .22 caliber rifle whs\nlying across his chest and the cov\ners were drawn over his body. A\nnote was found near the body\naddressed to his wife, to the ef\nfect that she had listened to out\nside gossip, had left him, and that\nhe was proving his love for her\nand his children.\nThe deceased had been mar\nried for some years, but, accord\ning to report, he and his wife did\nnot get along well together. She\nhad left him about two weeks\nbefore the suicide, going to her\nfather\u2019s home and taking the two\nchildren with her. His parents\nstate that he had gone more than\nonce to persuade her to return\nbut had not succeeded. The last\nvisit was on the evening of Jan\nuary 11th. He had been depress\ned and had remarked to a fellow\nworker that he intended to kill\nhimself if his wife did not re\nturn.\nRaymond Reece was born in\nClintwood Feb. 5, 1911. He grew\nup in the town and took up the\ntrade of a mechanic when he\nreached manhood. He had been\nworking in the Baker mine near\nClinchco for the last two years.\nHe is survived by his immediate\nfamily, his parents, four broth\ners and four sisters.\nBurial was in the cemetery on\nHill Ridge, near the home of his\nwife, Sunday. Before the burial\nfuneral services were held in the\nVallley View church, with Rever\nends S. M. McFall, Enoch Rose\nand Charles Breder in attend\nance. Burial arrangements were\nIn charge of Clintwood Funeral\nHome, with floral offerings sup\nplied by the Mountain Florist.\nMail vour news in early\nTRUCK MINES ON\nWAY OUT, SAYS\nINSPECTOR\nMore of the truck mines in this\nsection are closing, and for good,\nstates Sam P. Wright, mine in\ninspector. Steel is being pulled\nfrom many of them, he says, and\nthey are being reported as per\nanently closed.\nThe effects of truck mines clos\nings are being shown in the\nsteadily falling sales of stores.\nNearly all truck mine workers\nspent money as they made it in\nthe neighborhood stores. Now\nthese workers are either out of\njobs or employed in other com\nmunities. Several of the smaller\nbusiness houses have thus been\nshut down, and the owners have\ngone away to work. The business\nrecession that hit this section in\nJuly continues its course, with\nunemployment at its highest fig\nure within several years.\nAnother factor throws it sha\ndow over business in Dickenson\nCounty. The mines of the estab\nlished coal corporations are in\nstalling more machinery, and,\ntherefore, using fewer men. Few\nlocal miners have the training to\noperate the machines. A great\nbody of the machine men have\nhomes in other places and are\nsending their savings away from\nhere.\nU. S. Employment Service fig\nures show a growing labor sur\nplus in Southwest Virginia. The\nsharp recession in the coalfields\npredicted more than a year ago\nby John Hopkins Hall, State La\nbor Commissioner, has definitely\ncome to pass. Two effects, already\nVisible, are a lowering of the\nstandards of living and a drop in\npopulation as families move else\nwhere.\nTruck Drivers Will\nContest Chimney\nCorner Law\nFourteen truck drivers, noticed\ninto court last week to answer\ncharges of overloading, secured\na postponement of the hearing un\ntil Feb. 1, when arrainged in trial\njustice court Tuesday.\nIt appears that there is no dis\npute as to the facts. The trucks\nwere hauling more weight than\nthe highway department deems\nadvisable on the road between\nClintwood and Lick Fork. It is\nunderstood that the truckers,\nthrough their attorney, S. H.\nSutherland, will contest the inter\npretation of the law, or the right\nof the highway department to\nmake laws.\nNEW BUSINESS OPENS AT\nGHOST ROCK VILLAGE\nA. A. Skeen, otherwise \u2018Shemp\u2019,\nhas become a businessman,' if not\na resident of the town of Ghost\nRock. He will supply the people\nof that community with groceries,\nhardware, dlothing and other var\nious and sundry items of merch\nandise. He is operating in the\nstore building vacated by \u201cHon\nest\u201d Tiv Mullins, and will doubt\nless expand as the community\ngrows.\nCHURCH NOTICE\nServices will be held at Pound\nRiver church Sunday night at\n6:30. The Mullins Family will be\npresent for the singing. Everyone\nis invited and all are welcome.\nf The Dimes March That Children May Walk","height":"25636","width":"17916"}}
